================================================================
RED ROBIN GOURMET BURGERS, INC. (NASDAQ: RRGB)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended April 19, 2026
(Form 10-Q, filed May 19, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Revenue declined to $378.3m in Q1 FY26 from $392.4m in Q1 FY25, a (3.6%) / ($14.1m) YoY decrease, driven by restaurant closures (6 units in Q1 FY26 against ~50 closed cumulatively over the prior three years) and (0.6%) comparable restaurant sales (a (1.6%) guest traffic decline partially offset by a 1.0% higher average check, with the 3.1% price increase offset by (2.1%) mix/discount erosion as the Big Yummm value menu at $9.99–$16.99 reached 13%+ of sales). Full-year FY25 revenue was $1,210.2m vs $1,248.6m in FY24, a (3.1%) / ($38.4m) YoY decline; management reaffirmed FY26 guidance of 0.5%–1.5% comparable revenue growth, 13.0% restaurant-level operating profit margin, $70m–$73m Adjusted EBITDA, and $25m–$30m capex.

> Profitability: Restaurant-level operating profit margin (gross margin proxy for restaurant industry) expanded to 14.8% in Q1 FY26 from 14.3% in Q1 FY25, up 50 bps and marking the strongest Q1 restaurant-level margin in five years, driven by a 130 bps improvement in labour costs to 35.7% of sales (lowest Q1 labour percentage in three years) under the First Choice Plan operational efficiency programme. Consolidated operating margin contracted to 1.5% in Q1 FY26 from 2.3% in Q1 FY25, an 80 bps deterioration with income from operations declining to $5.5m from $9.1m, primarily reflecting $4.8m of "other charges" related to closure and restructuring activity (vs $0.7m in Q1 FY25) and elevated marketing spending behind the Big Yummm value platform. Net loss was ($2.2m) in Q1 FY26 versus net income of $1.2m in Q1 FY25, a $3.4m YoY swing driven by the higher other charges and continued interest burden of $7.8m for the quarter; Adjusted EBITDA was $27.3m, only marginally down from $27.9m in Q1 FY25. Full-year FY25 context: restaurant-level operating profit margin was 12.7% (vs 10.8% in FY24, +190 bps), consolidated operating margin was 0.2% (vs (4.3%) in FY24, +450 bps swing from operating loss to small operating profit), and net loss was ($23.3m) (vs ($77.5m) in FY24, a $54.2m improvement); the FY25 turnaround was material, but the Q1 FY26 print confirms the margin trajectory has plateaued.

> Cash Flows: Q1 FY26 cash from operating activities is not separately broken out in the earnings release, but the balance-sheet movement (cash of $24m, plus a sequential $5.5m increase in borrowings to $175.7m) implies net cash absorption in the quarter — consistent with seasonal Q1 working-capital patterns in casual dining, elevated marketing investment behind the Big Yummm platform, and continued capex against the $25m–$30m FY26 guidance envelope. For full-year FY25, the Company generated sufficient cash to reduce borrowings by approximately $20.3m, supporting the improved profitability narrative — but FY26 has reopened the revolver draw cycle.

> Liquidity and debt position: As of April 19, 2026, outstanding borrowings under the credit facility were $175.7m and liquidity was approximately $40.8m — a sequential erosion of $16.1m from the $56.9m liquidity position at FY25 year-end (December 28, 2025) and structurally thin for a $1.2bn-revenue chain. The composition of liquidity per the Q1 FY26 transcript was $24m in cash, $10m in restricted cash, plus $17m undrawn borrowing capacity on the revolver. The credit agreement had been amended to extend maturity to September 2027, and the Company retained Jefferies for refinancing — confirming that the current capital structure is viewed as transitional and that a more durable refinancing solution is being actively explored; the balance sheet also carries negative shareholders' equity, consistent with the multi-year accumulated deficit position.

> Working Capital: Working capital position remained tight, with the seasonal Q1 build offset by limited cash generation. Restaurant closures (6 units in Q1, expected to reach approximately 20 for the full year, with closures evenly distributed over the remaining three quarters) are providing one-time working-capital releases via lease terminations and asset sales, but the underlying operating working-capital base continues to depend on supplier credit terms and revolver availability rather than internally generated free cash flow. The unhedged commodity exposure flagged by management — 60% of 2026 commodity needs locked but beef and dairy remain mostly unhedged — represents a near-term margin and inventory-cost risk that could compound working-capital pressure if input prices accelerate.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: The "First Choice Plan" launched in mid-2025 is the active turnaround vehicle, comprising four operational pillars: (i) restaurant footprint rationalisation (~20 closures targeted for FY26 on top of ~50 cumulative closures over the prior three years), (ii) value-platform expansion (Big Yummm at 13%+ of sales), (iii) labour efficiency (130 bps Q1 FY26 reduction), and (iv) refranchising of company-owned units. Refranchising is in final-stage negotiations with several potential franchisees, with proceeds expected to be used for debt reduction and balance-sheet strengthening; refranchising upside is explicitly excluded from FY26 guidance, providing potential incremental deleveraging optionality. G&A discipline is also tracking, with full-year FY26 G&A guided to $65m–$67m versus FY25 G&A (excluding stock-based compensation) of $71m.

> Going Concern: The Q1 FY26 Form 10-Q does not include an explicit "substantial doubt" statement. However, the combination of negative shareholders' equity, persistent net losses despite the FY25 operational rebound, and a credit facility maturing in September 2027 with Jefferies engaged for refinancing represents a restructuring-adjacent risk profile that is materially comparable to going-concern stress scenarios. Execution risk on (a) the refranchising transaction signing and proceeds size, (b) the FY26 EBITDA achievement against the $70m–$73m guide, and (c) the refinancing of the credit facility before September 2027 will determine whether formal going-concern language is avoided in subsequent filings.

> Management Change: Significant senior finance leadership turnover during the lookback period. Mark Graff was appointed Chief Financial Officer effective May 4, 2026, succeeding interim CFO Christopher (Chris) Meyer, who joined in December 2025; Meyer had served on an interim basis after the departure of Todd Wilson, who became CFO of BJ's Restaurants. Graff joins from Bloomin' Brands where he led a $900m business as President of Bonefish Grill and Fine Dining. This is the third occupant of the CFO seat within roughly six months — a clear instability signal during a period of refinancing and turnaround execution. President & CEO Dave Pace remains in place as principal architect of the First Choice Plan.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged — the Q1 FY26 Form 10-Q was filed on May 19, 2026 within the statutory deadline, with no Form 12b-25 extension reported. The FY25 Form 10-K and Q4 FY25 earnings release were similarly on schedule on February 25, 2026. Reporting controls remain intact despite underlying balance-sheet stress and CFO turnover.

> Recent Issues & Restructuring-Relevant Developments: Material multi-year pattern of labor and regulatory litigation creating ongoing contingent liability and HR-controls overhang. Most recent and material: in August 2025, a California federal court granted final approval to a $3.2m wage class-action settlement (Case No. 8:17-cv-01422, U.S. District Court Central District of California) resolving allegations that Red Robin misclassified assistant and kitchen managers as overtime-exempt despite performing the same tasks as non-exempt workers. This sits on top of a prior pattern: (i) a $600,000 EEOC settlement (April 2024) for sexual harassment and retaliation involving teenage female employees across 12 Washington-state locations (EEOC v. Red Robin International, Inc., Case No. 2:22-cv-01378), under a three-year court-approved consent decree requiring engagement of a third-party EEO compliance reviewer for policies, investigations, and training; (ii) a $2.95m settlement in the Eastern District of New York resolving overtime claims by nearly 500 managers and assistant managers (Outlaw v. Red Robin); (iii) a $400k+ settlement with the Seattle Office of Labor Standards for alleged wage theft (December 2022); (iv) an $8.5m California wage and hour class-action settlement (2020); and (v) a $450k consumer class action settlement on Stella Artois serving sizes (August 2024). The Q1 FY26 10-Q discloses $0.1m of additional accruals for ongoing legal matters and notes "various claims in process, matters in litigation, administrative proceedings, and other contingencies… employment related claims and class action lawsuits, claims from guests or team members alleging illness, injury, food quality, health, or operational concerns, and lease and other commercial disputes." Operational pattern from litigation: chronic lean-staffing model relying on "secondary managers" performing non-exempt work — directly tied to the labour-cost efficiency programme touted in earnings calls. Commodity exposure: management disclosed only 60% of 2026 commodity needs are locked, with beef and dairy mostly unhedged — input cost volatility could compound margin pressure. Material 10-Q disclosure also notes 22 cumulative company-owned location closures during the FY26 footprint optimisation programme, with associated lease-termination and impairment charges flowing through "other charges."

